title: Grateful Dead Live at Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum on 1991-12-30
lineage: 16 bit – 48kHz DAT Master > TASCAM DA-20 (SPDIF out) -> LynxTWO-B Audio Reference Interface (SPDIF in) -> Wavelab 6.0 by Todd Evans Editing and Mastering: Jamie Waddell on the GEMS Edit Station. description:
Set 1

Touch Of Gray, Victim Or The Crime, Row Jimmy, Big River-> Maggie's Farm, Ramble On Rose, Just Like Tom Thumb's Blues, Bird Song-> Promised Land

Set 2

China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider, Samson & Delilah, Ship of Fools, Saint Of Circumstance-> Jam*-> Drums-> Jam-> The Last Time-> Stella Blue-> Turn On Your Love Light, E: The Weight

*Dear Prudence Jam

reviews.review_text: Airto Moreira! Thanx Marcus, James, and Jamie.  I was at this show and have not heard it since.  Sounds nice, punchy first set and some nice moments with Airto as he joins them for Saint thru Space and also Stella.  I am opening my radio show this week with China>Rider & Space thru Lovelight.  Peace

Who Needs Soundboards? 
When you have audience recordings such as this.
Thank you, GEMS. Thank you, Archives.org

Like the recording by the same people on the 28th and Litzenberger's AUD of NYE, I can answer that no one needs SBD's.

Unfortunately, for nearly two decades, the bass was very difficult for most portable microphones to handle. For me, the problem of older AUD's is just that, for the most part, they have muddy bass response. I can put up with tape flips but if Phil ain't there, I am probably not there.

Which is what I loved about the 1990-91 era shows. The recording technology had made incredible breakthroughs. By 1990 just about every taper had some high fallutin' recording mikes and DAT recorders. It really makes a difference.

The 30th doesn't have the same energy that the 28th and the 31st have. Band sounded tired. But tired or not they still sounded great. Ah, technology! I have always maintained that the sound was the most important factor in judging a show. If it sounds good, I can go along with subpar performance.

Nonetheless, after sleepwalking through Bird Song they seem to awaken and a Promised kicks it up a notch to end the first set and then there's a nice little China Rider to begin set two. Most of the rest is sorta daydream do-able.

If not for Phil's raging giant tractor beam bass this stuff would be rather pedestrian. It's what Jerry feeds off of. Over the years, many Heads got bored with Samson. Yes, it's sort of like NFA or Iko: once yer done with hearing that beat you just don't care if you hear it again. Yeah, but if you hear that bass guitar -- holy cow, Phil.

Jerry sings "40 years upon my head to have you call me child" on an eloquent SOF while his Irwin III "Rosebud" squawks away like the flight of giant condor.

Considering the band is so tired, Saint is pretty jovial and then they drift into a very sweet and pleasant jam. I guess this is what is referred to as the "Dear Prudence" nod. It is not Dear Prudence, IMO, it is just a spar of phrasing that the band got held up in like web.

Then comes Airto and his passionate percussion and catterwall, howl and grunts. It's all good. If one can cop to digging Airto then one can cop to being cool. His exhibition grants me license. 

YA JUS' GO FOR IT, PEOPLE !!!

OWWWW-WHOOOOO!!!

Truly the jam>airto>drumz>airtojam>  is the highlight of this show. Most beautiful drums/space segment ever. Hearkens back to Phil & Ned, but there is nothing more decidedly beautiful and drop dead gorgeous as this jam. Wow, I can't get over how I am raving about a drums jam. Then Jerry cuts in towards the middle and you can sense the heart-pouring oozing out of his sphere-ick persona. Then, one by one, the rest of the band's fall about him like children plopped 'neath a Lone Ranger radio show, the simultaneous sound of every ringing telephone in the cosmos.

And thankfully, thankfully, thankfully dropping adroitly down into The Last Time. This song is so messed up it's totally ebullient. Best song of the night ~ no doubt about it. Phil like to tear your heart asunder. From there...Stella Blue. A God's-owned Stella blue. A Stella for the ages. OMG ! Am I still alive? Somebody pinch me !! 

Somewhere, over the rainbow...

Oof. Back in Kansas. The Weight. A Weight so heavy.

But heck, it sounds good enough to me! WTF! I'm easy. And I know the band was always trying to do its best. I heard the heart of what they played. 

These nearly pristine AUD's allow us to hear the heart.

The heart of what is played.
